item.title: Effects of difficult arithmetic expressions or formulas in java or any language
item.dc:creator: @_s11 s1gma
item.description:
@_s11 wrote:

[quote=“The Wanderer, post:14, topic:441957”]I was looking into big O notation and there were some symbols I had no experience of (only had formal teaching up to alg 2, but plan on learning some pre calc and calc this summer), do you mind giving a short explanation of it? Would gladly appreciate it.[/quote]in most usages you see big O notation used to describe time complexity, which is roughly how many steps an algorithm takes to return a result given an input

so, an algorithm with O(1) time complexity (constant) supposedly only takes 1 step to return a value regardless of input.
an example is a simple add function:

int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }

meanwhile, an algorithm with O(n) time complexity (linear) will take n steps dependent upon something about the input.
a good example is array traversal where n describes the size of the array.

int[] doubleElements(int[] intArray) { for (int i = 0; i < intArray.length; i++) intArray[i] *= 2; return intArray; }

there are lots of different types of complexities ie. logarithmic, exponential etc. big O can also describe another type of complexity, space complexity, which shows how much space an algorithm needs in memory.

what are the symbols you’re stuck with?

item.title: Effects of difficult arithmetic expressions or formulas in java or any language
item.dc:creator: @Fat_Cookies Fat Cookies
item.description:
@Fat_Cookies wrote:

I’m not going to compile the code and look at the bytecode, but I’m pretty sure the java compiler would somehow optimize it so it’s not doing 10 million consecutive additions, etc etc.

The actual number of arithmetic instructions isn’t normally that important, it’s how the number of them increases as you increase the size of the input, hence why people measure an algorithms efficiency using the Big O notation. Anything in linear time O(n), logarithmic time O(log n) is a win, quadratic algorithms O(n^2) can get slow, any any exponential ( O(2^n) etc etc) is just painful.

Using any time methods in java to work out how long something takes is not reliable, shouldn’t be used to benchmark anything.

item.title: Effects of difficult arithmetic expressions or formulas in java or any language
item.dc:creator: @eyeownyew Eyeownyew
item.description:
@eyeownyew wrote:

[code] long now = System.currentTimeMillis();
long start = now;

int x = 0;
for(int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
	x += 45.1344;
}
System.out.println("Addition: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-now));

now = System.currentTimeMillis();
for(int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
	x -= 45.1344;
}
System.out.println("Subtraction: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-now));

now = System.currentTimeMillis();
for(int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
	x *= 1.325;
}
System.out.println("Multiplication: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-now));

now = System.currentTimeMillis();
for(int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
	x /= 1.325;
}
System.out.println("Division: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-now));
	now = System.currentTimeMillis();
for(int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
	x = (int)Math.round(Math.pow(x,1.325));
}
System.out.println("Exponent: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-now));
System.out.println("Total: "+(System.currentTimeMillis()-start));[/code]

This produced these results in ms… Total of 10 million loops in each math category, btw. That should never be realistically necessary Addition: 141 Subtraction: 125 Multiplication: 109 Division: 156 Exponent: 1219 Total: 1750
Even with 10 million loops of exponents and rounding, it took just over a second. Also, my hardware is awful, and once again, 10 million loops will never be realistically necessary.

Also, keep in mind that I could make this much faster with multithreading. The full time would be the time of the longest process, being exponents, rounding & casting put together
